---
import CourseLayout from '../../layouts/CourseLayout.astro';

const sections = [
  { id: 'post-training', label: 'Post-Training' },
  { id: 'prompting', label: 'Prompting & Reasoning' },
  { id: 'evaluating', label: 'Evaluating & Choosing Models' },
];
---

<CourseLayout
  day={2}
  title="From Models to Tools"
  description="Post-training alignment, prompting strategies, and how to evaluate and choose the right model for your research."
  sections={sections}
>

  <!-- ===== POST-TRAINING ===== -->
  <section id="post-training">
    <h2>Post-Training</h2>
    <p>
      A raw pretrained language model is a powerful next-token predictor, but it
      is not yet a useful <em>assistant</em>. Post-training bridges this gap
      through techniques that align the model's behavior with human preferences
      and instructions.
    </p>

    <div class="definition-box">
      <p class="definition-box__label">Definition</p>
      <p class="definition-box__term">Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT)</p>
      <p>
        Training a pretrained model on curated (instruction, response) pairs to
        teach it the format and style of helpful, task-oriented responses. SFT
        is typically the first step of post-training alignment.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p>
      After SFT, further alignment is achieved through reinforcement learning
      from human feedback (RLHF) or its simpler alternative, Direct Preference
      Optimization (DPO). These methods train the model to prefer outputs that
      humans rate as more helpful, honest, and harmless.
    </p>

    <div class="key-takeaway">
      <p class="key-takeaway__label">Key Takeaway</p>
      <p>
        Post-training is what turns a language model into a tool. Understanding
        this pipeline (SFT → RLHF/DPO) helps explain model behavior: why models
        sometimes refuse requests, why they hedge, and how alignment interacts
        with the research tasks you ask them to perform.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== PROMPTING ===== -->
  <section id="prompting">
    <h2>Prompting &amp; Reasoning</h2>
    <p>
      How you frame a request to a language model dramatically affects the
      quality of its output. Prompting has evolved from a practical trick to a
      principled engineering discipline.
    </p>

    <p>
      The progression from zero-shot to few-shot to chain-of-thought prompting
      represents increasingly structured ways of eliciting model capabilities.
      Structured outputs&mdash;asking the model to respond in JSON or follow a
      specific schema&mdash;are critical for research pipelines that need
      machine-parseable results.
    </p>

    <div class="stop-and-think">
      <div class="stop-and-think__header">
        <svg class="stop-and-think__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
          <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/>
          <path d="M9.09 9a3 3 0 0 1 5.83 1c0 2-3 3-3 3"/>
          <line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/>
        </svg>
        <span class="stop-and-think__label">Stop and Think</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        You're designing a prompt to classify political speeches as populist or
        non-populist. Would you use zero-shot, few-shot, or chain-of-thought
        prompting? What are the trade-offs?
      </p>
      <details>
        <summary>Reveal</summary>
        <div>
          <p>
            Few-shot with chain-of-thought is likely best. Zero-shot risks
            inconsistent criteria; few-shot examples anchor the model's
            understanding of your specific definition of populism; chain-of-thought
            reasoning makes the classification rationale transparent and auditable.
            The trade-off is token cost and latency per classification.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== EVALUATING MODELS ===== -->
  <section id="evaluating">
    <h2>Evaluating &amp; Choosing Models</h2>
    <p>
      The landscape of available models is vast: open-weight vs. proprietary,
      small vs. large, general-purpose vs. specialized. Choosing the right model
      for a research task requires understanding benchmarks, cost-quality
      trade-offs, and the strengths of different model families.
    </p>

    <p>
      Standard benchmarks like MMLU, HumanEval, and LMSYS Chatbot Arena give
      rough rankings, but research tasks often have idiosyncratic requirements
      that benchmarks do not capture. We cover systematic approaches to model
      evaluation for social science use cases.
    </p>

    <div class="key-takeaway">
      <p class="key-takeaway__label">Key Takeaway</p>
      <p>
        No single model is best for everything. The right choice depends on your
        task complexity, data sensitivity, budget, and need for reproducibility.
        Open models offer transparency and control; closed APIs offer
        convenience and often better performance on general tasks.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</CourseLayout>
